# Domain Model Conventions

The domain is pure Java: no Spring, no Mongo, no annotations, no records, no Lombok.

## Value object pattern

Every value object follows this exact shape (see `CriterionWeight`, `Score`, `ProductId`):

```java
public final class CriterionWeight {

    private final double value;

    public CriterionWeight(double value) {
        if (value < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Criterion weight cannot be negative");
        }
        this.value = value;
    }

    public double value() { ... }          // accessor named value(), no get prefix

    @Override public boolean equals(Object other) { ... }  // value-based
    @Override public int hashCode() { ... }
    @Override public String toString() { ... }
}
```

- `final` class, all fields `private final`, no setters. Defensive-copy collections and expose them unmodifiable.
- Invariants validated in the constructor with `IllegalArgumentException` and a human-readable message. These messages reach API clients as the 400 body, so word them carefully and assert them in tests.
- Behavior lives next to the data (`Stock.availabilityRatio()`, `Score.add()`), not in services. Use domain services (e.g. `ProductRankingService`) only for logic spanning multiple aggregates.
- `Product` is the aggregate root: equality by `ProductId` only. Value objects: equality by all values.
- Scores use `double` (relative ordering, not money). `Score` rejects `NaN`/`Infinity`; rounding happens only in the REST mapper.
